# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bill-rigney
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bill-rigney/1946-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1946 throughout the world.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-in-baseball-p01] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The **1946 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1946.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 3, with the St.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals defeated the Brooklyn Dodgers in a regular season best-of-three tiebreaker, for the National League title, after both teams finished their 154-game schedules with identical 96–58 records.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] It was Major League Baseball's first-ever regular season tie-breaker.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 43rd World Series on October 6 and ended with Game 7 on October 15.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals defeated the Red Sox, four games to three, capturing their sixth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1944.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Detroit Tigers from the 1945 season.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The 13th All-Star Game was held on July 9 at Fenway Park in Boston, Massachusetts, hosted by the Boston Red Sox.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] Many notable ballplayers returned from their military service this season, following the end of World War II, such as Joe DiMaggio, Stan Musial, and Ted Williams.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season in which the minor-league baseball color line broke.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] With the support from then-incoming commissioner Happy Chandler, Brooklyn Dodgers general manager Branch Rickey signed Jackie Robinson in late-October 1945 to their top minor-league affiliate, the Montreal Royals.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] Robinson would play for the Royals for the 1946 season.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last National and American League seasons to be played under the color barrier, as in the following season, Jackie Robinson would make his debut with the NL's Brooklyn Dodgers to start and Larry Doby would make his debut with the AL's Cleveland Indians in July.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The 1946 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 16, featuring all sixteen teams, continuing the trend from the previous season.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the scheduled regular season was on September 29, which saw all sixteen teams play, the first time since 1944.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals finishing with the same record of 96–58, a best-of-three tie-breaker was scheduled, to be considered an extension of the regular season.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals swept the series in two games, on October 1 & 3.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 6 and October 15.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] 9 tie games (5 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 15 with the St.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals defeating the Boston Red Sox in the 1946 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Indians would play their last game at League Park on September 21 against the Detroit Tigers, permanently moving into Cleveland Stadium for the start of the 1947 season.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] Over 77 home games, the Indians played 41 games at Cleveland Stadium and 36 games at League Park.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] All Sunday home games took place at Cleveland Stadium.
[src:bill-rigney/1946-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the last of 12 seasons since 1932 that saw the Indians play at both venues.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The **1947 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1947.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 28, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 44th World Series on September 30 and ended with Game 7 on October 6.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this Subway Series World Series matchup, the Yankees defeated the Dodgers, four games to three, capturing their 11th championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1943.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the St.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The 14th All-Star Game was held on July 8 at Wrigley Field in Chicago, Illinois, home of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The 1947 season is most notable as the year that the baseball color line broke, thanks to the Brooklyn Dodgers starting Jackie Robinson on Opening Day.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] On April 15, Opening Day for the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers, Jackie Robinson was in the Dodgers' lineup, playing first base against the Boston Braves at Ebbets Field.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] His appearance in a major league game broke the baseball color line, the practice of excluding players of black African descent.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Though he endured epithets and death threats, as well as a slow start, his skill would earn him the first ever Rookie of the Year award, named in Robinson's honor 40 years later.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Halfway through the season on July 5, the American League's Cleveland Indians debuted Larry Doby, becoming the first black player in the American League and breaking the AL color line.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Doby was a more low-key figure, suffered many of the same indignities that Robinson did, albeit with less press coverage.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Kansas City Monarchs star Willard Brown and teammate Hank Thompson briefly played for the St.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns, becoming the third and fourth Black players in either the NL or AL, and made the St.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns the first of either the NL or AL to field two Black players on one roster.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Brown was the first black player to hit a home run in the American League.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The 1947 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 15, featuring all sixteen teams, continuing the trend from 1945.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 28, which also saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend from the previous season.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first time since 1940 that all sixteen teams played their first and last games on the same days.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 30 and October 6.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] 11 tie games (7 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 30 and ended on October 6 with the New York Yankees defeating the Brooklyn Dodgers in the 1947 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the Indians would typically play home games at League Park on weekdays and Cleveland Stadium on weekends.
[src:bill-rigney/1947-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play at Cleveland Stadium for a total of 60 seasons through 1993.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1948 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 15th playing of the midsummer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 13, 1948, at Sportsman's Park in St.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis, Missouri, the home of both the St.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Browns of the American League (who were the designated host team) and the St.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the American League defeating the National League 5–2.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was the first All-Star Game to be broadcast on television, albeit only locally.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Richie Ashburn became only the third rookie player in MLB history to start in an All-Star Game after Joe DiMaggio, (1939) and Dick Wakefield, (1943).
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The lone representative of the host team was Al Zarilla, a reserve outfielder for the AL, who entered the game playing right field in the top of the 5th inning, and was hitless in two at bats.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Berry and Reardon swapped positions, also Stewart and Paparella swapped positions.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL scored two runs in the top of the 1st inning, on a leadoff single by rookie Richie Ashburn, and later a two-run home run by Stan Musial with one out.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It would be the only runs the NL would score.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL got one run back in the bottom of the 2nd inning, on a home run by Hoot Evers.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] They later tied the score at 2–2 in the bottom of the 3rd, after two walks, a steal of third base by Mickey Vernon, and a sacrifice fly from Lou Boudreau.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the bottom of the 4th, the AL pulled ahead with 3 runs; after loading the bases with two singles and a walk, Vic Raschi drove in two runs with a single, followed by one more run scoring on a lineout by Joe DiMaggio.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the AL up 5–2, there would be no more scoring, despite the NL loading the bases in the 6th inning.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The **1948 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1948.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 4, with the Boston Braves and Cleveland Indians as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The Indians won the American League title via a tie-breaker game victory over the Boston Red Sox, after both teams finished their 154-game schedules with identical 96–58 records.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second regular season tie-breaker, and saw a change from the previous three-game format to that of a single-game, Game 163.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 45th World Series on October 6 and ended with Game 6 on October 11.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The Indians defeated the Braves, four games to two, capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1920.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1947 season.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The 15th All-Star Game was held on July 13 at Sportsman's Park in St.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The American League won, 5–2, for their third straight win.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The 1948 season is notable as being the final season of any Negro league holding major-league status, as per MLB's 2020 designation of Negro leagues.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] It would be the final season of the Negro National League, while the Negro American League would continue as a minor-league until it ceased play after the 1962 season.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The 1948 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19, featuring six teams.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the scheduled regular season was on October 3, which saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend from 1946.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] Due to the Boston Red Sox and Cleveland Indians finishing with the same record of 96–58, a tie-breaker game was scheduled, to be considered an extension of the regular season.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The Indians won the Game 163 tie-breaker on October 4.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 6 and October 11.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] 7 tie games (3 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-rigney/1948-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 11 with the Cleveland Indians defeating the Boston Braves in the 1948 World Series in six games.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1951 throughout the world.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-in-baseball-p01] Baseball's Shot Heard 'Round the World gives the New York Giants the National League Pennant in the third game of a best-of-three-games tiebreaker series over the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-in-baseball-p01] Although the Negro American League would last until 1960, 1951 was, notably, the last season in which the Negro American League was considered major-league caliber, which was itself the last major Negro league baseball organization.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-in-baseball-p01] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The **1951 World Series** matched the two-time defending champion New York Yankees against the New York Giants, who had won the National League pennant in a thrilling three-game playoff with the Brooklyn Dodgers on the legendary home run by Bobby Thomson (the Shot Heard 'Round the World).
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] In the Series, the Yankees showed some power of their own, including Gil McDougald's grand slam home run in Game 5, at the Polo Grounds.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The Yankees won the Series in six games, for their third straight title and 14th overall.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] This would be the last World Series for Joe DiMaggio, who retired afterward, and the first for rookies Willie Mays and Mickey Mantle.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] This was the last Subway Series the Giants played in.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Both teams would meet again eleven years later after the Giants relocated to San Francisco.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] They have not played a World Series against each other since.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] This was the first World Series announced by Bob Sheppard, who was in his first year as Yankee Stadium's public address announcer.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] It was also the first World Series to be televised exclusively by one network (NBC) as well as the first to be televised nationwide, as coaxial cable had recently linked both coasts.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] This World Series also matched up two of baseball's most colorful managers, Casey Stengel of the Yankees and Leo Durocher of the Giants.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] This was the 13th appearance by the Giants in Series play, their ninth loss, and their first appearance since the 1937 World Series.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Mantle's bad luck with injuries in the Major Leagues began here.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] In the fifth inning of Game 2 at Yankee Stadium, Mays flied to deep right center.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] DiMaggio and Mantle converged on the ball, DiMaggio called Mantle off, and Mantle stutter-stepped, catching a cleat in a drain cover, and fell to the ground in a heap with a wrenched knee as DiMaggio made the catch.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Mantle was done for this Series, but would come back to play many more.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] New York City became the first city to host an NBA Finals and a World Series in the same calendar year.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Monte Irvin's daring baserunning got the Giants off to a fast start in this New York – New York series.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] He singled in the first inning, sped to third on Whitey Lockman's RBI single, then stole home off Yankee starter Allie Reynolds.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The Yankees cut the Giants' lead to 2–1 in the second when Gil McDougald doubled with one out off Dave Koslo and scored on Jerry Coleman's single.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The scored remained that way until the sixth when Alvin Dark's three-run home run gave the Giants a commanding 5–1 lead.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Koslo pitched a complete game to give the Giants a 1–0 series lead.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The first three batters Larry Jansen faced were Mickey Mantle, Phil Rizzuto and Gil McDougald, all of whom singled for a quick 1-0 Yankee lead.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] It could have been worse, but the next batter Joe DiMaggio bounced into a 6-4-3 double play and Yogi Berra struck out.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The next inning, Joe Collins's home run extended the Yankees' lead to 2–0.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] In the fifth Willie Mays flied out to Joe DiMaggio, who waved off right fielder Mantle, who got his spikes caught in an exposed drain and injured his knee and had to leave the game.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] This injury would stick with him for the rest of his career.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Monte Irvin scored in the seventh, tagging and coming home on pinch-hitter Bill Rigney's bases-loaded sacrifice fly, as the Giants got within 2–1.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] But winning pitcher Eddie Lopat, who pitched a complete game, helped himself to an insurance run with an RBI single in the eighth after Bobby Brown hit a leadoff single and moved to second on a groundout off George Spencer.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The Yankees' 3–1 win tied the series shifting to the Polo Grounds.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The Giants struck first in Game 3 when Bobby Thomson hit a leadoff double and scored on Willie Mays' single in the second, then a five-run fifth inning was the undoing of Yankee starter Vic Raschi.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Eddie Stanky walked with one out, moved to third on an error, and scored on Al Dark's single.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] After a Hank Thompson single, another error on Monte Irvin's fielder's choice allowed another run to score and put two on, then a Whitey Lockman three-run home run gave Giants starter Jim Hearn a comfortable 6–0 lead.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the eighth on a bases-loaded walk to Joe Collins, then in the ninth on Gene Woodling's home run off Sheldon Jones, who retired the next two batters to end the game and give the Giants a 2–1 series lead.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] In the rain-delayed Game 4, the Giants again scored first when Al Dark doubled with one out in the opening inning off Allie Reynolds and scored on Monte Irvin's single, but the Yankees tied the game in the second on Joe Collins's RBI single with two on off Sal Maglie.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] After a single and walk, Reynolds's RBI single in the fourth put the Yankees up 2–1.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Joe DiMaggio's first home run of the Series (and the last of his career) following a Yogi Berra single in the fifth extended their lead to 4–1.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] In the seventh, reliever Sheldon Jones allowed a single and walk, then an error on a pickoff attempt allowed one run to score before Gil McDougald's RBI single made it 6–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Reynolds allowed a one-out RBI single to Bobby Thomson in the ninth before getting Willie Mays to hit into the game-ending double play as the Yankees tied the series with a 6–2 win.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] After two one-out walks in the third, Joe DiMaggio's RBI single tied the game, then after an intentional walk loaded the bases, Gil McDougald's grand slam off Jansen put the Yankees up 5–1.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Next inning, Phil Rizzuto's home run off Kennedy after a walk extended their lead to 7–1.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] In the sixth, Rizzuto singled off Spencer before Yogi Berra's single and Johnny Mize's double scored a run each, making it 9–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] In the seventh, a bases-loaded walk to Rizzuto forced in a run, then Al Corwin threw a wild pitch that let another run score before DiMaggio's two-run double capped the game's scoring at 13–1 Yankees, who were a win away from the World Series championship as the series returned to Yankee Stadium.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The Yankees struck first in Game 6 on Gil McDougald's bases-loaded sacrifice fly in the first off Dave Koslo.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The Giants tied the game in the fifth off Vic Raschi when Willie Mays hit a leadoff single, moved two bases on a wild pitch and sacrifice fly, and scored on Eddie Stanky's sacrifice fly.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Playing right field in place of Mickey Mantle, Hank Bauer benefited from a tricky Yankee Stadium wind—as well as the umpire's generous call of a ball on Dave Koslo's two-strike pitch—to belt a bases-loaded triple in the sixth inning that would be the difference.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Bauer also ensured that the lead held up.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Trailing 4–1 in the ninth, the Giants loaded the bases with no outs on three singles off Johnny Sain.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Enter reliever Bob Kuzava, acquired in June from the Washington Senators.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] After two sacrifice flies and the score now 4–3, pinch hitter Sal Yvars hit a sinking liner to right.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] The stadium crowd gasped as Bauer momentarily lost the ball in the crowd's white shirts and the shadows.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] But he located it again and charged forward.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Bauer, who played in nine World Series and always came through when it mattered most, slid on his knees to catch the ball inches off the ground to end the game and the 1951 World Series.
[src:bill-rigney/1951-world-series] Game 6 was the last baseball game ever played by Joe DiMaggio.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] The San Francisco Bay Area native began his managerial career with the Giants and served as the team's last manager in New York City (1957) and its first in San Francisco (1958).
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] In 1961, Rigney became the first manager in the history of the Los Angeles Angels of the American League, serving until May of 1969.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Then, in 1970, he managed the Minnesota Twins to the AL West division championship, the only postseason entry of his big-league tenure.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Fired midseason in 1972, he concluded his managerial career in 1976 by serving a one-year term at the helm of his original team, the Giants.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Born in Alameda, California, Rigney batted and threw right-handed, stood 6 feet 1 inch (1.85 m) tall and weighed 178 pounds (81 kg).
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] He began his professional baseball career in 1938 when he signed with the unaffiliated Oakland Oaks of the top-level Pacific Coast League.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] After seasoning in the Class B Western International League, Rigney played the full seasons of 1941 and 1942 with the Oaks, then performed World War II service in the United States Coast Guard from 1943–1945.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Acquired by the Giants during the war, he was a 28-year-old rookie in 1946 and played third base, shortstop and second base during his MLB career—appearing in over 100 games played in each of his first four MLB seasons.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Rigney was the Giants' regular third baseman in 1946 and their starting second baseman in both 1947 and 1948.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] His most productive season came in 1947, when he reached career highs in home runs (17), runs batted in (59), runs (84), hits (142), doubles (24) and games played (130).
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] In 1948, he was selected to the National League All-Star team; in the 1948 midsummer classic, on July 13 at Sportsman's Park, St.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Louis, he drew a base on balls off Joe Coleman in his only plate appearance.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] On August 12, 1950, Rigney replaced Eddie Stanky at second base after Stanky had been ejected from a game against the Phillies for repeatedly waving his arms while Andy Seminick was batting.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Seminick was still irritated, and after he reached base on an error in the fourth inning, he slid hard into second base, crashing into Rigney and causing him to fall over.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] A nearly ten-minute brawl erupted between the teams, which required police intervention and resulted in the ejection of Seminick and Rigney from the game.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] As a utility infielder, Rigney was a member of the 1951 NL champion Giants, and he appeared in four games of the 1951 World Series, collecting one hit in four at bats (a single off Vic Raschi), with one run batted in, as a pinch hitter.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] As a big-leaguer, Rigney was a .259 career batsman with 510 hits, 41 home runs and 212 runs batted in over 654 games.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Following his MLB playing career, Rigney was named manager of the Giants' top farm club, the Triple-A Minneapolis Millers, in 1954–1955.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] He led the Millers to two playoff appearances, a 170–135 overall record, and the 1955 American Association and Junior World Series championships.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] He then was promoted to skipper of the parent Giants in 1956, succeeding his mentor, Leo Durocher.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] But upon their move to San Francisco in 1958—and rejuvenated by young players such as Orlando Cepeda, Jim Davenport, Felipe Alou, and, later, Willie McCovey—the Giants returned to the first division and contended for the NL pennant into the final regular-season weekend in 1959.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] The 1960 Giants moved into new Candlestick Park and were expected to again contend for the league title.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] They got off the mark quickly, winning 20 of their first 29 games.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] But then they stumbled, losing 16 of their next 29, and were coming off a three-game series sweep at home by the eventual world champion Pittsburgh Pirates when, on June 17, Rigney was fired.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] At 33–25, his club was in second place, four games behind Pittsburgh, when Rigney was dismissed.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Tom Sheehan, the veteran scout who replaced Rigney, fared even more poorly, however, going only 46–50 as the Giants plummeted into fifth place by season's end.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] He became the first skipper in the history of the expansion Los Angeles Angels of the American League in 1961.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Reynolds, the Angels' owners, originally wanted to hire future Baseball Hall of Fame manager Casey Stengel, a resident of nearby Glendale who had been fired by the New York Yankees after the 1960 World Series.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] But Stengel declined all managerial offers and spent 1961 in temporary retirement.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Then Durocher, out of uniform since leaving the Giants in 1955 and working as a broadcaster, campaigned for the Angel job.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Like Stengel, he had become a permanent resident of Southern California—he lived in Palm Springs—and was a future Hall of Fame pilot.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] But Autry and Reynolds bypassed him and chose Rigney instead, believing that he would have the patience to develop an expansion team's younger players.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] While the Angels' maiden edition lost 91 games and finished eighth in the ten-team AL, the 1962 team, paced by young pitchers Dean Chance and Bo Belinsky, stunned baseball by finishing in third place with an 86–76 record during their second season of existence.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] As a result, Rigney was named Manager of the Year by The Sporting News.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] During Rigney's eight full years with the Angels, the club played in three home ballparks—Wrigley Field, Dodger Stadium and Anaheim Stadium—and also compiled winning records in 1964 and 1967.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] But 1969, Rigney's ninth season, proved catastrophic.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] The Angels started the year 11–28 and were mired in a ten-game losing streak when Rigney was fired on May 27 and succeeded by Lefty Phillips.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Later in 1969, Rigney joined the San Francisco Giants' radio broadcast team to close out the season; coincidentally, KSFO, the Giants flagship station, was then owned by Autry and Reynolds.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Returning to the field (and to the Twin Cities of Minneapolis–St.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Paul) the next year, Rigney succeeded Billy Martin as manager of the Minnesota Twins in 1970, leading them to 98 victories and the American League West Division championship.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] But the Twins fell in three straight games to the eventual world champion Baltimore Orioles in the 1970 American League Championship Series, then won only 74 games in 1971.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] When the Twins began 1972 with a 36–34 record and 91⁄2 games behind the eventual World Series champion Oakland Athletics in third place, Rigney was replaced by Frank Quilici on July 6.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] After serving as a scout for the San Diego Padres and California Angels (1973–1974), Rigney had a second managerial stint with the Giants in 1976, a year of transition between the Horace Stoneham and Bob Lurie ownerships.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Rigney's 1976 club went only 74–88 and finished 28 games behind the world champion Cincinnati Reds.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Joe Altobelli succeeded him at the Giants' helm on October 7, 1976.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Rigney finished with a managerial record of 1,239 wins and 1,321 losses.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] The Twins' three-and-out loss in the 1970 ALCS was his only MLB postseason managing appearance.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] As a minor league pilot, Rigney won the 1955 American Association championship at the helm of the Minneapolis Millers.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] After leaving the Giants at the close of his second managerial term in 1976, he served as a front-office consultant and a radio and television broadcaster for the Oakland Athletics in the 1980s.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] Rigney died in Walnut Creek, California, at age of 83.
[src:bill-rigney/bill-rigney] The "Bill Rigney Good Guy Award" is given each year to a Bay-Area MLB player who is most accommodating to the media.
